**Explanation of consistent Stats() snapshot:**

The `Stats()` method acquires `p.mu` (a standard mutex) before reading any mutable state. This ensures that `InFlight` (protected by the mutex) and `QueueDepth` (derived from `len(p.taskQueue)`, which is also mutated only while holding the mutex) are read atomically with respect to each other. The counters `TotalSubmitted`, `TotalCompleted`, `TotalPanics`, and `TotalRejected` are updated with `atomic.AddInt64` and read with `atomic.LoadInt64` while holding the mutex, providing a consistent point-in-time view. The mutex prevents torn reads between the queue length and in-flight count, which could otherwise change between two atomic loads. This design gives a consistent snapshot without needing to lock all operations (the hot path of task execution uses the mutex only briefly for in-flight bookkeeping).
